                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Columbyne Celebfin wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">OK, I've seen in a few places statements along these lines--that an enchanter needs to *jack up* their own aggro and that will help the tank hold aggro.  Maybe it's because I don't play a tank, but for the life of me I haven't been able to figure this one out...obviously I am mis-understanding how aggro and taunt work.  How can one character having huge amounts of aggro help another character get aggro?  Can someone explain this to me in simple terms so I get it?  <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /></td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
How taunt is <span style="text-decoration: underline">suppose</span> to work is give the taunter the highest amount of aggro on the mobs chart + 1 (edit - so if chanter has the highest aggro, say 500, warrior with successful taunt gets 500 + 1 or 501 and moves to the top of the list). Taunt does not work every time, has a very short range, and obviously gives a taunter little room to work with (which is why warriors are in such an uproar about being raid tanks only). Failed taunt is said to give the same aggro as a missed swing (not sure on this).
<br />

<br />
We chanters can build aggro pretty darn well (understatement, yes). The goal of most people is to not get aggro, specially a class such as ours that isnt overly suited to taking a beating. However, if performed properly (and the dice rolls your way), you can solve a warriors aggro issues fairly easily. Pull with tash, run beside warrior. Can go two routes here depending on survivability chances of the chanter. Either taunt  right away or wait for slow as well. Taunt has a 6 second refresh time, so def have to work with that. Test aggro by slowly backin away, if warrior has aggro, mob wont turn for you. If it does, stay put until you lose aggro.
<br />

<br />
Yes, dangerous game to play with hard hitting mobs. I am a 60 chanter, so dont have ER or AR and I dont use rune5, but have done this successfully in tier1, was only after I had grouped with the warrior for a bit that I asked if he wanted to try it (aka, I had some faith in his abilities). I wasnt able to do this when I first hit pop, but once I upped my HPs more (after learning they are very important) I found I could do the above...but would only attempt with a warrior I trusted.
<br />

<br />
Side Note - Spamming Taunt doesnt do a darn thing (save increase chance of skill ups). Getting your own aggro + 1 doesnt amount to much of a difference. Maybe my math is wrong...maybe  <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="icon_razz.gif" border="0" /> .</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />~ <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=583742" target="_blank" class="postlink">Phreza Bum</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
