                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Phreza ... you put a smile on my face today, thank you.
<br />

<br />
Just to take it one step further:
<br />

<br />
Jacking your aggro up as high as possible assists the MT in holding aggro, not against the enchanter but against the rest of the group.
<br />

<br />
So, for example, in LDoN, mobs burn down VERY quickly!  If a caster has to wait for the mob to be at 80% health before opening up then the mob is as likely to die before they land anything.
<br />

<br />
An enchanter, doing his job properly, can bootstrap the MTs aggro up dramatically upon a successful taunt.
<br />

<br />
1. Greater Fetter
<br />
2. Tash
<br />
3. Slow
<br />
4. Cripple (If useful)
<br />

<br />
Then hold the mob, if possible, using Greater Fetter (because your mezz can blur which will lose you the aggro generated by the first mezz and everything cast before it), by the time the tank gets to it and successfully taunts the mob will have massive aggro on the tank.
<br />

<br />
The rest of the party starts out far behind the MT and can open up on the mob immediately after the successful taunt.
<br />

<br />
Now, how does this affect the enchanter in question?  
<br />

<br />
Well, having a 1000 aggro and 1 aggro is essentially the same thing BEFORE the mob is engaged.  So if the mob breaks mezz or root, it will be heading your way (depending on its aggro type).  So BEFORE engage whether you blur a mob or not is immaterial really.
<br />

<br />
AFTER engage, there are 2 ways the tank will gain the mobs attention.  Either he will damage the mob enough that the tanks aggro climbs higher than yours or he will taunt and thus gain aggro higher than yours.
<br />

<br />
The trade off here is surviving long enough for the tank to get a successful taunt and thus surpassing your aggro vs blurring your aggro down so low that the first blow by the tank places him higher on the aggro list than you.  One option is good for the enchanter but causes complications with the rest of the party and the other method helps the rest of the party while subjecting the enchanter to a higher level of risk.
<br />

<br />
A good tank will turn and engage/taunt the next mob on his engage list before the previous mob dies and rely upon the rest of the group to finish off the almost dead mob while the new mob is being "prepared" for the rest of the group.
<br />

<br />
This means that MOST of the time, before the party finishes off the old mob and switches to the new one, the MT has taunted twice and has secured aggro.  Thus the when the other party members lob that first nuke that breaks your root the tank should have aggro.
<br />

<br />
If he does not and does not gain it before the root breaks then the mob in question is slowed so you should be able to survive long enough for the MT to taunt it off you.
<br />

<br />
I never blur mobs and only ever boggle mobs once the MT has secured aggro via Taunt and I wish to Nuke or DOT.
<br />

<br />
NOTE: For mobs that cannot be rooted, substitute mezz for root.
<br />

<br />
How to help your tank gain aggro 101.  
<br />

<br />
No wonder Warrior taunt does not work well in this new EQ because every high aggro class has the ability to reduce aggro which does not help the Taunter much at all.
<br />

<br />
Regards,</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Sage <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=370213" target="_blank" class="postlink">Zanithar TideBreaker</a> - Coercer
<br />
<a href="http://www.therelentless.com" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Relentless</a>, Cazic Thule
